  "method": "We propose Parallel Draft–Verify Decoding (PDVD): a small draft model D proposes a block of the next B tokens in parallel, and the large target model L verifies and commits a maximal prefix of that block, guaranteeing the exact output that L would have produced under the chosen decoding policy (greedy or stochastic). At each step, we maintain L’s KV cache for the accepted prefix. D is a lightweight transformer trained to approximate L’s next-token distribution and, crucially, to predict the next B positions simultaneously using a lookahead masking scheme so its B predictions can be produced in one pass.\n\nDrafting: Given prefix x1:t, we append B masked slots and run D once with a position-specific lookahead mask that prevents the masked slots from attending to each other, letting every future position see the same prefix but not cross-talk with other future positions. D outputs logits (or top-m lists) for positions t+1..t+B in parallel; we sample or select candidates from these logits according to the downstream decoding policy (e.g., greedy or temperature sampling) to form a draft block ŷ1:B.\n\nVerification: We run L autoregressively over the draft block reusing the KV cache, but stop as soon as we encounter the first position j where D’s draft and L’s policy disagree. For greedy decoding, we accept all ŷ1:(j−1) that match L and set yj to L’s argmax; for stochastic decoding, we perform acceptance–rejection at each position i using the standard probability ratio test min(1, pL(yi|x, y< i)/pD(yi|x, y< i)), which yields exact samples from L. To save compute when a mismatch is likely, we add a shallow verifier gate g that inspects early-layer activations and D’s logits to predict rejection; if g flags a likely mismatch at position i, we abort the deep layers for that position and mark it as a rejection early, while still running the full L pass for any token we finally commit—preserving exactness.\n\nScheduling and pipelining: While L verifies the current block, D immediately drafts the next block from the (temporarily) extended context, keeping both models busy. Across a batch of sequences, we verify blocks in a strided, GPU-friendly manner. To further increase parallelism without changing correctness, maintain a cache of tentative tokens across future steps and iterate in sweeps: each sweep lets L verify only its assigned positions (earliest unverified positions across requests) using cached guesses elsewhere; after the sweep, we write back accepted tokens and repeat. This converges to the same sequence as fully sequential decoding, yet enables high hardware utilization via batched verification.\n\nTraining D and the verifier gate: Train D via distillation from L on next-token prediction and a blockwise objective: for randomly chosen prefixes, predict the next B tokens with the lookahead mask so every position learns to rely solely on the prefix. Train the shallow gate g to predict “accept vs reject” using features from early L layers and D’s logits, with a loss that heavily penalizes false accepts; at inference, g only short-circuits expensive verification on tokens that would be rejected, never on tokens we ultimately commit.",
  "rationale": "This design eliminates quality loss by committing tokens only after L has validated them, and by using exact acceptance–rejection for stochastic decoding. The small D amortizes the expensive large-model passes: if the average accepted-prefix length per draft is r·B (r = acceptance rate), then L performs one forward sweep per r·B emitted tokens instead of per token, yielding a speedup of roughly 1/r in the large-model compute, while D’s parallel draft is cheap and overlapped. The verifier gate further reduces wasted large-model work by aborting deep-layer computation early on blocks that will be rejected, without changing any committed outputs.\n\nThe lookahead masking allows D to produce multiple future positions in a single pass without causal leakage between those positions, which is what makes parallel drafting both valid and efficient. The iterative, cache-based scheduling maintains high device utilization and mirrors a fixed-point view of sequential decoding: multiple tentative positions are updated and corrected until they match L’s true trajectory, but tokens are only emitted once L has fully verified them—preserving exact equivalence to L’s outputs.",
