  "method": "We propose Draft-Verify Parallel Decoding (DVPD): a two-model pipeline where a small draft model D speculatively proposes multi-token continuations in parallel and the large model L verifies them with a single batched forward pass. At each step, D produces a short draft block of length m along a greedy path and optionally a few branched alternatives per position (small branching factor b). L is then run once on the packed set of proposed tokens under teacher forcing to obtain conditional probabilities for every proposed position. A per-token accept/reject rule is applied left-to-right to accept the longest prefix whose drafted tokens pass verification; on the first rejection, we immediately emit L’s own token for that position, discard the remaining drafted suffix, and continue. The accept/reject test is implemented as a correction step that makes the emitted token distribution exactly match L’s sampler, ensuring no quality loss relative to decoding with L alone. KV caches computed during verification are retained so accepted tokens never require recomputation.\n\nTo make drafts highly verifiable, we train D by distilling multi-step conditionals from L. D uses a lightweight backbone and M parallel heads to predict up to M future tokens from the current prefix (depth-m drafting). The loss combines next-token KL with multi-step teacher-forced KL over the drafted depth, plus a calibration auxiliary head that predicts a per-token acceptance probability from D’s pre-softmax activations. During training, uncertainty-aware weighting up-weights examples and positions where D is less confident and/or disagrees with L, improving calibration and downstream acceptance rates without increasing D’s size.\n\nAt inference, DVPD adapts its drafting budget to context difficulty. The confidence head estimates an acceptance curve over the next positions; we choose the draft depth m and branching b to keep the expected number of accepted tokens per verification above a target. A tiny selector then ranks the few branched candidates by cumulative confidence and prunes to the top-K proposals before verification, keeping the large-model batch small and dense. Verification is early-terminating: we accept tokens until the first rejection; because L was run on the whole packed set once, this becomes a cheap, linear-time check over the positions with no additional L calls. While L verifies the current block, D asynchronously prepares the next draft from the most recently accepted prefix, overlapping compute and further reducing wall-clock latency.\n\nEngineering-wise, we pack proposals sharing a prefix into a single L forward using a block attention mask and contiguous token layout so the GPU sees one dense batch. We reuse L’s KV cache from the prefix; accepted tokens simply extend the cache, and even on rejection we retain the cache up to the rejection point. If D’s accuracy drops (e.g., out-of-domain context), the controller shrinks m and prunes branching to avoid wasted verification, and in the limit DVPD reverts to pure L decoding. Because emitted tokens are either accepted under the exact correction rule or sampled directly from L at the rejection point, DVPD preserves L’s output distribution by construction.\n\nThis end-to-end procedure yields large speedups when D’s drafts often match L, amortizing one L pass over multiple emitted tokens. Dynamic confidence-gated drafting and selective verification keep the acceptance rate high and the verifier batch small, while exact correction guarantees that output quality is indistinguishable from decoding with L alone.",
  "rationale": "Sequential LLM decoding is slow because each emitted token demands a full large-model step. DVPD increases tokens-per-L-forward by letting a small, parallel-friendly draft model propose multiple future tokens at once and then verifies them in a single, early-terminating large-model pass. When drafts match, several tokens are accepted with no further large-model work; when they do not, the acceptance test falls back to L’s own sample at the first mismatch and continues, so there is no degradation in output distribution or quality.\n\nTwo additional mechanisms improve efficiency without hurting accuracy: a tiny selector prunes low-value branches before verification, and an uncertainty-calibrated controller adapts draft depth and branching to context difficulty to maintain a high acceptance rate. Together, these keep large-model compute focused on the most promising candidates and prevent regressions when the draft model is uncertain or out-of-domain, while cache reuse ensures no redundant large-model computation for accepted tokens.",
